hamenei (r. 1989-present) the supreme leader of the Islamic Republic. This book engages with E’tesami in the transformational context of the early twentieth century in Iran to investigate the controversies around her identity as a popular female poet. It demonstrates that the reason for E’tesami’s paradoxical popularity was not merely her gender, but the transgression of patriarchal Iranian-Muslim gender norms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Iran.2bisacsh  aParvin E'tesami, Classical Persian Poetry, Persian debate poetry (mun.ara), transgression, Iranian-Muslim gender norms, patriarchy, socio-political criticism, mystic-didactic poetry, politics and poetry, mysticism.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400604575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400604575/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles